      <div class="col-sm-7">
        <h2></h2>
        
            <div class="gen-group">
              
              <div class="gen-group__content">
                <p class="subheading">Site managed by</p>
                <h2>Resilient Energy Alvington Court Renewables</h2>
              </div>
            </div>
        
        <div class="gen-content">
          <p>Resilient Energy Alvington Court Renewables Ltd is a community benefit society that owns and operates the community wind turbine at Alvington Court farm in the Forest of Dean, Gloucestershire. The project is owned by 177 shareholders ranging in age from 18 to 84, the majority being from the local Gloucestershire/South Wales area. </p>
<p>The project is a newly installed 500kW wind turbine, operational since November 2015. Developed by The Resilience Centre, using its Resilient Energy model, the project is on a small family farm along the Severn Estuary that is already affected by climate change, losing 40 acres of salt marsh grazing to sea level rise and inundation. The project is helping the farmer tackle these issues by diversifying farming activity and providing additional income.</p>
<p>As a community benefit society, all of the surplus from the project, estimated to be up to £1.5-2 million over its operational life, will be used to create resilience within the local community, tackling issues such as fuel poverty, climate change and community regeneration. </p>
<p>Annual revenue from the sale of energy will be used to repay community and social investors with all surplus being directed into two community funds. A local grant fund of approximately £15,000-£20,000/year donated annually to the parishes of Alvington and Aylburton, where the turbine is, as decided by a self-appointed local community panel. The additional surplus, an estimated £1,000,000+, will go into a second fund to remove 250+ homes from fuel poverty, and provide seed funding for other community renewable energy projects within the Forest of Dean District, an area identified as being in the worst 10% of areas for fuel poverty in the UK.</p>
          <p class="read-more"><a href="#" class="button">Read More</a></p>
        </div>
        

